We recommended the Management the strict compliance with rules set forth by Republic Act (RA) No. 9184, to:

Ensure that the procurement procedures are religiously followed;

Use non-discretionary pass/fail criteria especially during bid evaluation and/or opening of bids;
Secure performance securities from the winning bidder before signing of contract;
Exert extra caution or close watch with the details of performance securities, surety bonds and other documents, particularly, its validity;

Direct the BAC to require the concerned Contractors to submit an irrevocable standby letters of credit of from a commercial bank, bank guarantees or surety bonds callable on demand equivalent to the retention money of 10 per cent of the 50 per cent of the value of works and furnish the Auditor a copy thereof and require the Municipal Accountant to deduct retention money of 10 per cent from every progress payment until 50 per cent of the value of works, as determined by the procuring entity, are completed.  If, after 50 per cent completion, the work is satisfactorily done and on schedule, no additional retention shall be made; otherwise, the 10 per cent retention shall be imposed.
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to submit suspension orders or any documents that would warrant the non-imposition of liquidated damages to the concerned contractor to the Office of the Municipal Accountant copy furnished the Audit Team, if any. Otherwise, direct the Municipal Accountant to compute the liquidated damages for the above-mentioned project;
Maximize the conduct of Pre-bid Conference to minimize the chances or possibilities of bidders’ disqualification due to non-compliance with the bidding requirements; 
Require the Municipal Engineer and/or Project Inspector or any employee of the agency mandated to supervise the implementation of the infrastructure projects of the agency to submit to the Audit Team copies of the Results of Test Analysis/Status of Quality Control Test or Quality program being implemented by the Municipality; and 
Direct the BAC to invite the observers on the procurement stage or activity within the prescribed period.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

Submit comment on why the projects were recommended for award upon opening of bids and prior to bid evaluation and post-qualification;

Submit valid justification on why the pre-bid conference was conducted not in accordance with the above mentioned act;

Submit valid justification on why the Construction Safety and Health Program approved by the DOLE was not part of the contract documents; and

Require the BAC to strictly adhere with the provision of the 2016 R-IRR of R.A. No. 9184.

